AGI - Panic in the Westfield mall in Sydney: a man armed with a knife attacked the present, killing five people and storing eight more, different in a serious way. A sixth person died then for the wounds reported. Among those who were brought to the hospital, also a mother and a small child. The police intervened and killed the assailant. At the moment the law enforcement forces "have no information" but "from the first investigations it would seem that it acted alone", said Deputy Commissioner Anthony Cooke at the press conference, underlining that "it continues to try to identify the author of the crime". As for motive, "I do not exclude anything", said Cooke, questioned on a possible terrorist track.
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
The alarm took place in the early afternoon, reported: at 15.20 local time the man entered the mall and began to attack people. A police inspector who was nearby intervened and chased it to the fifth floor of the building. He turned around, raised the knife and she shot him, killing him.<br> Tactical teams also intervened on the spot, a second potential attacker was talked about, but the news was denied. The crowd, panicked, was evacuated while the ambulances took away the wounded. Five dead, plus the attacker. Images turning on social media show the killer, dressed in shorts and sports shirt, move inside the building by branding a long knife. Another video shows a man trying to block it with a stake on the mobile stairs, people running and wounded on the ground in a blood bath.<br> &nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
Prime Minister Anthony Albanese was informed of the facts and in an improvised press conference he was called "dissolved", paying tribute to the police officer and civilians who tried to block the attacker. The scenes coming from the mall are "beyond words or understanding", "it's really shocking that this happens in a country like ours, where people should be able to shop on Saturday afternoon without thinking about the risks that this entails," he said, underlining that this "horrible act of violence" does not find place in a "peaceful lover" nation like Australia.
&nbsp;
<
<div </div
</div
&nbsp;
Cordoglio was also expressed by the New South Wales premier, Chris Minns, who said "unreached" for the event and thanked "the police, the emergency services, the first rescuers and the community for the courage shown in front of this shocking incident". A message to the families of the victims was also sent by opposition leader Peter Dutton, who wanted to emphasize that "in the horror of this afternoon there was also heroism", citing the agents and rescuers intervened, "in particular, the courage of a female agent who neutralized the aggressor".
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
&nbsp;

